        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-07-19T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-07-19T12:00:00-05:00" n="475"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d475">
                <head>475. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in the United
                        Kingdom</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d475fn1">Source: Department or State, Central
                        Files, 684A.86/7–1956. Secret. Received at 3:14 p.m. Repeated to Cairo and
                        Tel Aviv.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1956-07-19T18:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 19, 1956—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>344. Reference <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 247, July 13.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d475fn2">See <ref target="#d459fn3">footnote 3, Document
                        459</ref>.</note> Foreign Office tells Embassy that Lord <persName>John
                        Hope</persName> on July 17 delivered letter to <persName corresp="#p_HD1"
                        >Hammarskjold</persName>, who expressed appreciation for advance
                    information. He expressed general agreement with <persName corresp="#p_LJS1"
                        >Selwyn Lloyd</persName>’s views as contained in letter,<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d475fn3">A copy of <persName corresp="#p_LJS1">Lloyd</persName>’s
                        letter to <persName corresp="#p_HD1">Hammarskjold</persName>, dated July 14,
                        is attached to <persName corresp="#p_BWC1">Burdett</persName>’s memorandum
                        of a conversation on July 18 with <persName corresp="#p_BRW1"
                            >Bailey</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_MW1">Morris</persName> of
                        the British Embassy. (Department of State, <gloss target="#t_SS1"
                            >S/S</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_NEA1">NEA</gloss> Files: Lot 61 D 417,
                        Omega #9)</note> agreed he could probably undertake stage one and said he
                    shared <gloss target="#t_HMG1">HMG</gloss>’s misgivings regarding stage two. He
                    added that he would prefer not to be involved in stage two.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_AWW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Aldrich</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
